'''Richmond Park''' in south-west London was created by Charles I in the 17th century<ref name= Pastscape>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=397979|title=Richmond Park: National Monuments Record, Pastscape|publisher= [[English Heritage]]|accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> as a [[Medieval deer park|deer park]]. The largest of London's Royal Parks, it is of national and international importance for wildlife conservation. The park is a [[national nature reserves in England|national nature reserve]], a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] and a [[Special Area of Conservation]] and is included, at Grade I, on [[English Heritage]]'s [[Register of Historic Parks and Gardens of special historic interest in England]]. Its landscapes have inspired many famous artists and it has been a location for several films and TV series. 
[[File:Richmond Park understorey.jpg|thumb|The park is a [[national nature reserve (United Kingdom)|national nature reserve]].]]
[[File:Two deer at Richmond Park, London.jpg|thumb|[[Fallow deer]] in Richmond Park]]
[[File:Richmond Park, Beverley Brook - geograph.org.uk - 676367.jpg|thumb|[[Beverley Brook]] in the park]]
[[File:Adam's Pond, Richmond Park - geograph.org.uk - 1453459.jpg|thumb|Adams Pond]]

Richmond Park includes many buildings of architectural or historic interest. The Grade I-listed [[White Lodge]] was formerly a royal residence and is now home to the [[Royal Ballet School]]. The park's boundary walls and ten other buildings are listed at Grade II, including [[Pembroke Lodge]], the home of 19th-century British Prime Minister Lord [[John Russell, 1st Earl Russell|John Russell]] and his grandson, the philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]].

Historically the preserve of the monarch, the park is now open for all to use and includes a golf course and other facilities for sport and recreation. It played an important role in both World Wars and in the 1948 and 2012 Olympics.

==Size==
Richmond Park is the largest of London's Royal parks.<ref name="TRP">{{cite web | url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks| title=Parks | publisher=[[The Royal Parks]] | accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> It is the second largest park in London (after the 10,000 acre [[Lee Valley Park]], whose area extends beyond the [[M25 motorway|M25]] into [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Essex]]) and is Britain's second largest urban walled park after [[Sutton Park]],<ref name= "Hansard">{{cite web|author=[[Hansard|Department of the Official Report (Hansard)]], [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], [[Westminster]] |url= http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo020207/text/20207w18.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Written Answers for 7 Feb 2002 (pt 18) |publisher=www.parliament.uk |accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> [[Birmingham]]. Measuring 3.69 square miles (955 [[hectare]]s or 2,360 [[acre]]s),<ref name= "Hansard"/> it is comparable in size to [[Paris]]'s [[Bois de Vincennes]] (995 ha or 2,458 ac) and [[Bois de Boulogne]] (846 ha or 2,090 ac).<ref>Dominique Jarrass<U+00E9>, ''Grammaire des jardins Parisiens'', Parigramme 2007.</ref>  It is almost half the size of [[Casa de Campo]] ([[Madrid]]) (1750 ha or 4324.34 ac)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Instituto Geogr<U+00E1>fico Nacional de Espa<U+00F1>a|title=Visor cartogr<U+00E1>fico Iberpix|url=http://www2.ign.es/iberpix/visoriberpix/visorign.html|accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> and around three times the size of [[Central Park]] in New York (341 ha or 843 ac).<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ <U+2013> Central Park|url=http://www.centralpark.com/guide/faq.html|website=CentralPark.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>

==Status==
Of national and international importance for wildlife conservation, Richmond Park is a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magic.defra.gov.uk/MagicMap.aspx?startTopic=Designations&activelayer=sssiIndex&query=HYPERLINK%3D%271002388%27|publisher= [[Natural England]]|title= Map of Richmond Park SSSI}}</ref><ref name= "SSSI"/> a National Nature Reserve (NNR)<ref name=NNR>{{cite web |url= http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/nnr/regions/london.aspx |title= London NNRs |publisher= [[Natural England]]|accessdate= 20 June 2012}}</ref> and Special Area of Conservation (SAC).<ref name="JNCC">{{cite web | url= http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/protectedsites/sacselection/sac.asp?EUcode=UK0030246 | title=Richmond Park | publisher=[[Joint Nature Conservation Committee]] | accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="Management Plan 16-29 ">{{cite web | url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/41767/richmond-park-management-plan.pdf | title=Strategic Framework | publisher=[[The Royal Parks]] | work=Richmond Park Management Plan | date=January 2008 | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> The largest Site of Special Scientific Interest in London, it was designated as an SSSI in 1992,<ref name="SSSI">{{cite web | url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/1002388.pdf | title=Richmond Park | publisher=[[Natural England]] | work=Citation | date=1992 | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> excluding the area of the golf course, Pembroke Lodge Gardens and the Gate Gardens.<ref name="Management Plan 16-29"/> In its citation, [[Natural England]] said: "Richmond Park has been managed as a royal deer park since the seventeenth century, producing a range of habitats of value to wildlife. In particular, Richmond Park is of importance for its diverse deadwood beetle fauna associated with the ancient trees found throughout the parkland. In addition the Park supports the most extensive area of dry acid grassland in Greater London."<ref name="SSSI"/>

The park was designated as an SAC in April 2005 on account of its having "a large number of ancient trees with decaying timber. It is at the heart of the south London centre of distribution for stag beetle Lucanus cervus, and is a site of national importance for the conservation of the fauna of invertebrates associated with the decaying timber of ancient trees".<ref name="SAC selection">{{cite web | url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/protectedsites/sacselection/sac.asp?EUCode=UK0030246 | title=Richmond Park | publisher=[[Joint Nature Conservation Committee]] | work=SAC selection | date=2005 | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>

Since October 1987 the park has also been included, at Grade I,<ref name="English Heritage list">{{cite web | url=http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1000828 | title=List entry summary: Richmond Park | publisher=[[English Heritage]] | work=Heritage Protection | date=May 2002 | accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref> on the Register of Historic Parks and Gardens of special historic interest in England, being described in [[English Heritage]]'s listing as "A royal deer park with pre C15 origins, imparked by Charles I and improved by subsequent monarchs. A public open space since the mid C19".<ref name="EH Register">{{cite web | url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/caring/listing/registered-parks-and-gardens/ | title=Registered Parks and Gardens | publisher=[[English Heritage]] | accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref>

==Geography==
Richmond Park is located in the [[London Borough of Richmond]]. It is close to [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], [[Ham, London|Ham]], [[Kingston upon Thames]], [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], [[Roehampton]] and [[East Sheen]].<ref name= "Hansard"/>

{{Geographic Location
