'''The Friends of Richmond Park''' (FRP) was founded in 1961 to protect the park. In 1960 the [[speed limit]] in the park had been raised from 20 to 30 miles an hour and there were concerns that the roads in the park would be assigned to the main highway system as had recently happened in parts of [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]].<ref name= "Pollard and Crompton 2-3">Pollard and Crompton, pp. 2-3</ref> In 1969, plans by the then [[Greater London Council]] to assign the park's roads to the national highway were revealed by the Friends and subsequently withdrawn.<ref name= "Pollard and Crompton 9">Pollard and Crompton, p. 9</ref> The speed limit was reduced to 20 miles an hour in the summer of 2004.<ref name= "Pollard and Crompton 33">Pollard and Crompton, p. 33</ref>

In 2011, the Friends successfully campaigned for the withdrawal of plans for open air screenings of films in the park.<ref name="Auto6L-10">{{cite news|url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/richmondnews/9190284.Richmond_Park_cinema_plans_withdrawn/ |title= Richmond Park cinema plans withdrawn|work= Richmond Guardian|author=Paul Teed|date= 11 August 2011|accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="Auto6L-11">{{cite web|url=http://www.frp.org.uk/news/158-friends-oppose-park-screenings|title=Friends oppose Park screenings |publisher= [[Richmond Park#Friends of Richmond Park|Friends of Richmond Park]] website|date= 19 July 2011|accessdate= 28 June 2012}}</ref> In 2012, the Friends contributed towards the cost of a new Jubilee Pond, and launched a public appeal for a Ponds and Streams Conservation Programme in which the Friends, the Richmond Park Wildlife Group and Healthy Planet have been working with staff from The Royal Parks to restore some of the streams and ponds in the park.<ref name="Auto6L-13">{{cite web |url= http://www.stmgrts.org.uk/archives/2012/05/new_jubilee_pond_in_richmond_park_to_be_created.html|title=New Jubilee Pond in Richmond Park to be Created|publisher=[[St Margarets, London|St Margarets]] Community website|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Auto6L-14">{{cite news| url= http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/richmondnews/9699149.Jubilee_pond_to_open_in_Richmond_Park/ |title=Jubilee pond to open in Richmond Park|author= Christine Fleming|work=Richmond Guardian|date= 10 May 2012|accessdate= 5 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="More Ponds">{{cite web | url=http://www.frp.org.uk/news/225-work-starts-on-more-ponds | title=Work starts on more ponds | publisher=[[Richmond Park#Friends of Richmond Park|Friends of Richmond Park]] | year=2012 | accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>

The Friends run a visitor centre near Pembroke Lodge, organise a programme of walks<ref name="Auto6L-7">{{cite web |url= http://www.roehampton.ac.uk/Campus/Environment/Projects-and-Initiatives/Walking-Works/|title=Walking Works Campaign|publisher=[[University of Roehampton]]|year= 2012|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> and education activities for young people, and produce a quarterly newsletter. The Friends have published two books, ''A Guide to Richmond Park'' and ''Family Trails in Richmond Park''; profits from the books' sales contribute towards the Friends' conservation work.<ref name="Auto6L-8">{{Cite web |url= http://www.wandsworth.gov.uk/news/article/10356/new_guide_book_to_richmond_park |title=New guide book to Richmond Park|publisher=[[London Borough of Wandsworth]]|date= 28 March 2011|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="Auto6L-9">{{Cite news |url= http://www.frp.org.uk/pdf/news/170_SurreyComet_review_Sept_2011.pdf|title=Trails give us thrill of discovery|work= [[Surrey Comet]] |author=June Sampson|date= 2 September 2011|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>

The Friends of Richmond Park has been a charitable organisation since 2009.<ref name="50 years">{{cite news |url= http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/8927743.Friends_group_to_mark_50_years/|title=Friends of Richmond Park to mark 50 years of protecting the green space |author=Christine Fleming |work=Wandsworth Guardian |date=25 March 2011|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref> It has 2200 members, is run by approximately 150 volunteers and has no staff.<ref name= "50 years"/>  Broadcaster and naturalist David Attenborough, former Richmond Park MP Baroness [[Susan Kramer]] and children's author [[Dame Jacqueline Wilson]] are patrons of FRP.<ref name="AutoQO-4">{{cite news |url= http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/8949352.Sir_David_steps_up_at_park_party/|title= Sir David Attenborough steps up as Friends of Richmond Park marks golden anniversary|author= Christine Fleming|work= [[Richmond and Twickenham Times]]|date=3 April 2011|accessdate= 8 September 2014}}</ref> The chair (in 2015) is Ron Crompton, who also chairs the Royal Parks Friends Forum.<ref name="Regent's Park">{{cite web | url=http://www.friendsofregentspark.org/data/glaviewsmrbrowne.pdf | title=Greater London Authority: Mayor's Office | publisher=Friends of Regent's Park | work=Letter to Ron Crompton, chairman Friends of Richmond Park and Chairman, Royal Parks Friend Forum, from Anthony Browne, Chairman GLA Royal Parks working group | date=17 August 2010 | accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> The Friends Forum enables the chairs of all the Royal Parks Friends groups to meet regularly to discuss common issues and to make their views known to the chief executive of the Royal Parks, the Royal Parks Advisory Group and the Department of Culture, Media and Sport.<ref name="Greenwich">{{cite web | url=http://www.friendsofgreenwichpark.org.uk/index.php?page_id=38 | title=The Friends of the Royal Parks Forum ("Friends Forum") | publisher=Friends of [[Greenwich Park]] | accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>

