'''The Hearsum Collection''' is a registered charity<ref name="Charity 115301">{{cite web | url=http://opencharities.org/charities/1153010 | title=The Hearsum Collection | publisher=Open Charities | date=11 June 2014 | accessdate=3 November 2014}}Charity registration number 1153010</ref> that collects and preserves the heritage of Richmond Park. It has a collection, which was started in 1997,<ref name="Park History">{{cite web | url=http://www.pembroke-lodge.co.uk/richmond-park-history | title=Richmond Park History | publisher=[[Pembroke Lodge]] | accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> of heritage material covering the last four centuries, with over 5000 items including antique prints, paintings,<ref name="FRP blog"/> maps, postcards, photographs, documents, books and press cuttings. Volunteers from the Friends of Richmond Park have been cataloguing them.<ref name="FRP blog">{{cite web | url=http://blog.frp.org.uk/tag/hearsum/ | title=History Volunteers welcome new paintings of Richmond Park | publisher=Friends of Richmond Park | work=FRP blog | date=19 May 2013 | accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> The Collection, which as of 2015 continues to be stored in unsatisfactory accommodation in Pembroke Lodge,<ref name="Hearsum video"/> is overseen by volunteers and part-time staff. The trustees announced in 2014 plans for a new purpose-built heritage centre to provide full public access to the Collection.<ref name="Hearsum video"/><ref name="Hearsum">{{cite web | url=http://hearsumcollection.org.uk/ | title=Welcome to The Hearsum Collection | publisher=[[Richmond_Park#The_Hearsum_Collection|The Hearsum Collection]] | accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name="Guild">{{cite web | url=http://www.trpg.org.uk/history/history.php | title=Conserving Our Parks' Heritage | publisher=The Royal Parks Guild | accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name="Wood - heritage">{{cite journal | title=Consultation on  new heritage centre | author=Robert Wood | journal=Friends of Richmond Park newsletter |date=Autumn 2014  | page = 13}}</ref>

==Richmond Park in literature==
===Fiction===

====19th century====
Chapter 22 of George McDonald's novel ''The Marquis of Lossie'' (published in London in 1877 by [[Hurst and Blackett]])<ref name="Rees">{{cite book | url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ORW9F05auG0C&pg=PA153&dq=Hurst+and+Blackett+1877+The+Marquis+of+Lossie&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JLx5U_TtPMOwOYmngYgP&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Hurst%20and%20Blackett%201877%20The%20Marquis%20of%20Lossie&f=false | title=George McDonald | publisher=Twayne Publishers Inc | author=Richard H Rees | year=1972 | page=153}}</ref> is entitled "Richmond Park".<ref name="Lossie">{{cite web | url=http://www.readbookonline.net/read/19480/55669/ | title=Chapter 22. Richmond Park | work=The Marquis of Lossie | author= George McDonald|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref>

====20th century====

In [[Georgette Heyer]]'s [[Regency romance]] ''[[Sylvester, or the Wicked Uncle]]'' (1957) there is an expedition to Richmond Park.<ref name="Sylvester">{{cite book | title=[[Sylvester, or the Wicked Uncle]] | publisher=[[William Heinemann]] | author=[[Georgette Heyer]] | year=1957 | location=London|pages=193 and 197}}</ref>

====21st century====
Isabella Plantation in Richmond Park is the scene of a picnic and a child's disappearance in chapters 9 and 10 of [[Chris Cleave]]'s 2008 novel ''[[The Other Hand]]''.<ref>[[Chris Cleave]] (2008). ''[[The Other Hand]]'' (American title ''Little Bee''). London: [[Hodder & Stoughton]] paperback, pp. 300<U+2013>333.</ref> Richmond Park features in Jacqueline Wilson's novel ''[[Lily Alone]]'' (2010) and in the poetry anthology she edited, ''Green Glass Beads'' (2011).<ref name="Wilson">{{cite web | url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/yoursay/schools/9387275.print/ | title=Poems in Richmond Park | work=Richmond Guardian | date=26 November 2011 | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>

===Non-fiction===
''A Hind in Richmond Park'' by [[William Henry Hudson]], published in 1922 and republished in 2006, is an extended natural history essay. It includes an account of his visits to Richmond Park and a particular occasion when a young girl was struck by a red deer when she tried to feed it an acorn.<ref name="Hudson">{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/hindinrichmondpa00hud | title=A Hind in Richmond Park | author=[[William Henry Hudson]]| publisher=J M Dent and Sons Ltd | date=1922 | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>

==Richmond Park in art==

===Paintings, drawings and sculptures===

====17th century====

The [[oil painting]] ''The Carlile Family with Sir Justinian Isham in Richmond Park'' is held at [[Lamport Hall]] in [[Northamptonshire]].<ref name="BBC Carlile">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/the-carlile-family-with-sir-justinian-isham-in-richmond-pa49201 | title=The Carlile Family with Sir Justinian Isham in Richmond Park by Joan Carlile | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> It was painted by Joan Carlile (1600<U+2013>1679) who lived at Petersham Lodge.<ref name="Toynbee and Isham"/>

====18th and 19th centuries====

A portrait by T Stewart (a pupil of [[Sir Joshua Reynolds]]) in 1758 of ''John Lewis, Brewer of Richmond, Surrey'', whose legal action forced Princess Amelia to reinstate pedestrian access to the park, is in the Richmond upon Thames Borough Art Collection. It is on display in Richmond Reference Library.<ref name="BBC Lewis">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/john-lewis-brewer-of-richmond-surrey-87382 | title=John Lewis, Brewer of Richmond, Surrey | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>

[[Joseph William Allen|Joseph Allen]]'s ''Sir Robert Walpole (1676<U+2013>1745), 1st Earl of Orford, KG, as Ranger of Richmond Park (after Jonathan Richardson the Elder)'' is in the collection of the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], and is held at [[Erddig]], [[Wrexham]].<ref name= "BBC Allen">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/sir-robert-walpole-16761745-1st-earl-of-orford-kg-as-rang100111 | title=''Sir Robert Walpole (1676<U+2013>1745), 1st Earl of Orford, KG, as Ranger of Richmond Park'' (after Jonathan Richardson the Elder) by Joseph Allen | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> The painting is based on a portrait with a similar title, by [[Jonathan Richardson|Jonathan Richardson the Elder]] and [[John Wootton]], which is held at [[Norwich Castle| Norwich Castle Museum and Art Gallery]].<ref name= "BBC Richardson">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/sir-robert-walpole-1st-earl-of-orford-as-a-ranger-of-rich228923 | title= ''Sir Robert Walpole, 1st Earl of Orford, as a Ranger of Richmond Park'' by Jonathan Richardson the elder and John Wootton | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Thomas Rowlandson - Richmond Park - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|220px|''Richmond Park'' by [[Thomas Rowlandson]]]]
Artist and caricaturist [[Thomas Rowlandson]] (1756<U+2013>1827)'s drawing ''Richmond Park'' is at the [[Yale Center for British Art]].<ref name="Rowlandson">{{cite web | url=http://collections.britishart.yale.edu/vufind/Record/1669944 | title=Richmond Park | publisher=Yale Center for British Art | work=Thomas Rowlandson, 1756<U+2013>1827, British | accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>

''The Earl of Dysart's Family in Richmond Park'' by [[William Frederick Witherington]] (1785<U+2013>1865) is in The Hearsum Collection at Pembroke Lodge.<ref name="New paintings">{{cite web | url=http://blog.frp.org.uk/tag/painting/ | title=History Volunteers welcome new paintings of Richmond Park | publisher=[[Richmond Park#Friends of Richmond Park|Friends of Richmond Park]] | work=FRP blog | date=19 April 2013 | accessdate=15 July 2013 | author=Mary Pollard}}</ref>

''Landscape: View in Richmond Park'' was  painted in 1850 by the English Romantic painter [[John Martin (painter)|John Martin]]. It is held at the [[Fitzwilliam Museum]] in [[Cambridge]].<ref name="Martin BBC">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/landscape-view-in-richmond-park-5011 | title=''Landscape: View in Richmond Park'' | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

[[William Bennett (painter)|William Bennett]]'s [[watercolour]] ''In Richmond Park'', painted in 1852, is held by [[Tate Britain]]. It can be viewed, by appointment, at its Prints and Drawings Rooms.<ref name="Tate Bennett">{{cite web | url= http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/bennett-in-richmond-park-n01722 | title=William Bennett: ''In Richmond Park'' 1852 | publisher=[[Tate Gallery]] | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

''Landscape with Deer, Richmond Park'' (1875) by Alfred Dawson is in the [[Reading Museum]]'s collection.<ref name="Dawson BBC">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/landscape-with-deer-richmond-park-41588 | title= ''Landscape with Deer, Richmond Park'' | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>

[[John Buxton Knight]]'s ''White Lodge, Richmond Park'', painted in 1898, is in the collection of [[Leeds]] Museums and Galleries.<ref name="BBC Buxton Knight">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/white-lodge-richmond-park-38458 | title=''White Lodge, Richmond Park'' by John William Buxton Knight | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

====20th century====

The oil painting ''Richmond Park'' (1913) by Arthur George Bell is in the collection of the [[London Transport Museum]].<ref name="BBC Bell">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/richmond-park-215742 | title=''Richmond Park'' by Arthur George Bell| publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>

[[Spencer Frederick Gore|Spencer Gore]]'s painting ''Richmond Park'', thought to have been painted in the autumn of 1913 or shortly before the artist's death in March 1914, was exhibited at the Paterson and Carfax Gallery<ref name="Carfax">{{cite web | url= http://www.artbiogs.co.uk/2/galleries/carfax-gallery | title=Carfax Gallery | work=Artist Biographies: British and Irish Artists of the 20th Century | accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> in 1920. In 1939 it was exhibited in [[Warsaw]], [[Helsingfors]] and [[Stockholm]] by the [[British Council]] as ''Group of Trees''.<ref name="Tate 1">{{cite web | url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/gore-richmond-park-n05100 | title=''Spencer Gore: Richmond Park'' c.1914 | publisher=[[Tate Gallery]] | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> It is now in the collection of the [[Tate Gallery]] under its original title but is not currently on display.<ref name="Tate 1"/>  The painting is one of a series of landscapes painted in Richmond Park during the last months of Gore's life.<ref name="BBC Gore 1">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/richmond-park | title=''Richmond Park'' by Spencer Gore | publisher=[[BBC]] | work= Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> According to Tate curator Helena Bonett, Gore's early death from [[pneumonia]], two months before what would have been his 36th birthday, was brought on by his painting outdoors in Richmond Park in the cold and wet winter months.<ref name="Tate 2">{{cite web | url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/research-publications/camden-town-group/spencer-gore-r1105355 | title=Spencer Gore 1878<U+2013>1914 |  work= The Camden Town Group in Context|publisher=[[Tate Gallery]] | accessdate=7 February 2015 | author=Helena Bonett | date= September 2009}}</ref> It is not certain where in the park the picture was made but a row of trees close to the pond near Cambrian Gate has a very close resemblance to those in the painting.<ref name="Tate Upstone">{{cite web | url= http://www.tate.org.uk/art/research-publications/camden-town-group/spencer-gore-richmond-park-r1163001| title=Spencer Gore: ''Richmond Park'' c.1914 | publisher=[[Tate Gallery]] | work=The Camden Town Group in Context | date=May 2009 | accessdate=7 February 2015 | author=Robert Upstone}}</ref> Another Gore painting, with the same title (''Richmond Park''), painted in 1914, is at the Ashmolean Museum. His painting ''Wood in Richmond Park'' is in the [[Birmingham Art Gallery]]'s collection.<ref name="Wood in Richmond Park">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/wood-in-richmond-park-33967 | title=''Wood in Richmond Park'' by Spencer Gore | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

The oil painting ''Autumn, Richmond Park'' by [[Alfred James Munnings]] is at the [[Sir Alfred Munnings Art Museum]] in [[Colchester]].<ref name="BBC Munnings">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/autumn-richmond-park-3716 | title=''Autumn, Richmond Park'' by Alfred James Munnings | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

Chinese artist [[Chiang Yee]] wrote and illustrated several books while living in Britain.  ''Deer in Richmond Park'' is Plate V in his book ''[[The Silent Traveller in London]]'', published in 1938.<ref name="Chiang Yee V&A">{{cite journal | url= http://www.vam.ac.uk/content/journals/research-journal/issue-no.-4-summer-2012/the-silent-traveller-chiang-yee-in-britain-1933-55/ | title=The silent traveller: Chiang Yee in Britain 1933<U+2013>55 | author=Anna Wu | journal=V&A Online Journal |date=Summer 2012 | volume=4 | issue=ISSN 2043-667X}}</ref>

''Trees, Richmond Park, Surrey'', painted in 1938 by [[Sir Francis Cook, 4th Baronet|Francis Ferdinand Maurice Cook]], is in the Manchester City Galleries' collection.<ref name="BBC Cook">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/trees-richmond-park-surrey-204730 | title=''Trees, Richmond Park, Surrey'' by Francis Ferdinand Maurice Cook | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

[[Henry Moore]]'s oil painting ''In Richmond Park'' is in the collection of the [[York]] Museums Trust.<ref name="BBC Moore">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/in-richmond-park-8276 | title=''In Richmond Park'' by Henry Moore | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

''Richmond Park No 2'' by the English Impressionist painter [[Laura Knight]] is at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]].<ref name="BBC Knight">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/richmond-park-no-2 | title=''Richmond Park No.2'' (unsigned) by Laura Knight | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>

''In Richmond Park'' (1962) by James Andrew Wykeham Simons is at the [[University College London#Museums and collections|UCL Art Museum]].<ref name="BBC Simons">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/in-richmond-park-42421 | title=''In Richmond Park'' by James Andrew Wykeham Simons | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

[[Kenneth Armitage]] (1916<U+2013>2002) made a series of sculptures and drawings of oak trees in Richmond Park between 1975 and 1986.<ref name="Tate Armitage">{{cite web | url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/kenneth-armitage-664/text-artist-biography | title=Kenneth Armitage: artist biography | publisher=[[Tate Gallery]] | accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> His collage and etching ''Richmond Park: Tall Figure with Jerky Arms'' (1981) is in the British Government Art Collection and is on display at the British Embassy in [[Prague]].<ref name="Jerky">{{cite web | url=http://www.gac.culture.gov.uk/work.aspx?obj=10888 | title=Kenneth Armitage  - Richmond Park: Tall Figure with Jerky Arms | publisher=[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] | work=Government Art Collection | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> The Government Art Collection also holds his ''Richmond Park: Two Trees with White Trunks'' (1975), <ref name="White Trunks">{{cite web | url=http://www.gac.culture.gov.uk/work.aspx?obj=17357 | title=Kenneth Armitage - Richmond Park: Two Trees with White Trunks | publisher=[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] | work=Government Art Collection | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park: Five Trees, Grey Sky'' (1979)<ref name="Five Trees">{{cite web | url=http://www.gac.culture.gov.uk/work.aspx?obj=25290 | title=Kenneth Armitage -  Richmond Park: Five Trees, Grey Sky | publisher=[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] | work=Government Art Collection | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> and his sculpture ''Richmond Oak'' (1985<U+2013>86).<ref name="Richmond Oak">{{cite web | url=http://www.gac.culture.gov.uk/work.aspx?obj=12276 | title=Kenneth Armitage:  Richmond Oak | publisher=[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] | work=Government Art Collection | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>

''Richmond Park Morning, London'' (2004) by Bob Rankin is at [[Queen Mary's Hospital]], Roehampton,<ref name="BBC Rankin">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/mypaintings/rjw1214/my-collection#/14 | title=''Richmond Park Morning, London'' | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> which also holds a panel of five oil paintings by Yvonne Fletcher entitled ''Richmond Park, London'' (2005<U+2013>06).<ref name="BBC Fletcher">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/richmond-park-london-94968 | title=''Richmond Park, London'' (panel 2 of 5) by Yvonne Fletcher | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=Your paintings: Uncovering the nation's art collection | accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

===Historic posters===
[[File:The Lion.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[LMR 57 Lion|Lion]]'' (seen here in May 1980) masqueraded as ''Thunderbolt'' for the film ''Titfield Thunderbolt'']]
[[File:Richmond 2005 05 1ab.jpg|thumb|right |Park at [[Schloss Richmond|Richmond Castle, Brunswick]]]]
<!--HIDDEN PENDING INVESTIGATION OF DUBIOUS CLAIM "OWN WORK" [[File:Salim Ali Salam with King Faisal I of Iraq in Richmond Park in London in 1925, along with Salim's son Saeb and daughters Anbara and Rasha..jpg|thumb|right|[[Salim Ali Salam]] and [[King Faisal I of Iraq]] in the park in 1925, with Salim's son Saeb and daughters Anbara and Rasha]]-->
The [[Underground Electric Railways Company]] published, in 1911, a poster, ''Richmond Park'', designed by Charles Sharland. This is at the London Transport Museum,<ref name="Sharland">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?_IXSR_=mDsXZEBqECu&_IXMAXHITS_=1&IXinv=1983/4/114&IXsummary=results/results&IXsearch=richmond&_IXFIRST_=7 | title=Richmond Park, by Charles Sharland, 1911 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> which also has: a [[District line]] poster from 1908, ''Richmond Park for pleasure and fresh air'', by an unknown artist;<ref name="Unknown">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&IXinv=1983/4/14&IXsummary=results/results&IXsearch=richmond&_IXFIRST_=3 | title=Richmond Park for pleasure and fresh air, by unknown artist, 1908 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park'', by an unknown artist (1910);<ref name="Unknown 2">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=4 | title=Richmond Park, by unknown artist, 1910 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond by Underground'', by Alfred France (1910);<ref name="France">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=5 | title=Richmond by Underground, by Alfred France, 1910 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park'', by Arthur G Bell (1913);<ref name="Bell poster">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=11 | title=Richmond Park, by Arthur G Bell, 1913 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>  ''Richmond Park; humours no. 10'' by German American puppeteer and illustrator [[Tony Sarg]] (1913);<ref name="Sarg">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=12 | title=Richmond Park; humours no. 10, by Tony Sarg, 1913 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park by tram'', by Charles Sharland (1913);<ref name="Sharland 1913">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=13 | title=Richmond Park by tram, by Charles Sharland, 1913 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park'', by Harold L Oakley (1914);<ref name="Oakley">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=14 | title=Richmond Park, by Harold L Oakley, 1914 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Natural history of London; no. 3, herons at Richmond Park'', by Edwin Noble (1916);<ref name="Noble">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=17 | title=Natural history of London; no. 3, herons at Richmond Park'', by Edwin Noble (1916) | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park'' by Emilio Camilio Leopoldo Tafani (1920);<ref name="Tafani">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=18 | title=Richmond Park, by Emilio Camilio Leopoldo Tafani, 1920 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Rambles in Richmond Park'', by [[Freda Lingstrom]] (1924);<ref name="Lingstrom">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?design=abc&_IXSESSION_=3IoiZ5nGFfX&IXsearch=richmond&IXsummary=results/results&_IXSR_=91m_vc1O5jd&_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXFIRST_=23 | title=Rambles in Richmond Park, by Freda Lingstrom, 1924 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> ''Richmond Park'' by Charles Paine (1925);<ref name="Paine">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?_IXSR_=wD5NUjbe18V&_IXMAXHITS_=1&IXinv=1983/4/1790&IXsummary=artist/artist&IXartist=Charles%20Paine&_IXFIRST_=23 | title=Richmond Park, by Charles Paine, 1925 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> and ''Richmond Park'', a poster commissioned by [[London Transport Executive|London Transport]] in 1938 and illustrated by the artist Dame Laura Knight.<ref name="Knight 1938">{{cite web | url=http://www.ltmcollection.org/posters/poster/poster.html?_IXSR_=_qOTNWMPbqk&_IXMAXHITS_=1&IXinv=1983/4/5045&IXsummary=results/results&IXsearch=Richmond%20Park&_IXFIRST_=19 | title=Richmond Park, by Laura Knight, 1938 | publisher=[[London Transport Museum]] | work=Poster | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>

==Richmond Park on film==
Richmond Park has been a location for several films and TV series:

* A [[locomotive]] runs through the park and crashes into a tree in the film ''[[The Titfield Thunderbolt]]'' (1955).<ref name="Screen"/>

* In the 1968 film ''[[Performance (film)|Performance]]'', James Fox crosses Richmond Park in a Rolls Royce car.<ref name="Screen"/>

* The park was the backdrop for the classic historical film ''[[Anne of the Thousand Days]]'' (1969),<ref name="Star">{{cite web | url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/richmond-park/about-richmond-park/the-park-is-the-star | title=The Park is the star | publisher=[[The Royal Parks]] | work=Richmond Park | accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref> with [[Richard Burton]] and [[Genevi<U+00E8>ve Bujold|Genevieve Bujold]], which looks back to Richmond Park in the 16th century. The film tells the story of King Henry VIII's courtship of Anne Boleyn and their brief marriage.

* An Indian [[dust storm]] was filmed in the park for the film ''[[Heat and Dust]]'' (1983).<ref name="Screen">{{cite book | title=Richmond on Page and Screen | publisher=[[Museum of Richmond]] | authors=Sue Barber and Philippa Heath|editor= Valerie Boyes | title=Richmond on Screen: Feature Films Shot in the Borough | year=2009 | pages=27}}</ref>

* The Royal Ballet School in Richmond Park featured in the film ''[[Billy Elliot]]'' (2000).<ref name="Screen"/><ref name="Lydall">{{cite news | url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/billy-elliot-v-the-badgers-7086734.html | title=Billy Elliot v the badgers | work=[[Evening Standard]] | date=3 February 2005 | accessdate=18 October 2013 | author=Ross Lydall | location=London}}</ref>

* In 2011, director [[Guy Ritchie]] filmed parts of ''[[Sherlock Holmes (2009 film)|Sherlock Holmes 2]]'' in the park with [[Robert Downey, Jr.]] and [[Jude Law]].<ref name="Holmes">{{cite news | url= http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/richmondnews/8459315.Detective_sequel_filming_in_Richmond_Park/ | title=Richmond Park transformed into gypsy camp as Sherlock Holmes sequel starring Robert Downey Jr. as Sherlock and Jude Law as Dr Watson is filmed | work= [[Richmond and Twickenham Times]]|date=18 October 2010 | accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>

* Some of the scenes from ''[[Into the Woods (film)|Into the Woods]]'' (2014), the [[Disney]] fantasy film featuring [[Meryl Streep]],<ref name="Vincent">{{cite news | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/10339166/Meryl-Streep-in-Into-The-Woods-first-look.html | title=Meryl Streep in Into The Woods: first look | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=27 September 2013 | accessdate=13 February 2014 | author=Alice Vincent}}</ref> were filmed in the park.<ref name="Meryl Streep">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03qflhm | title=Meryl Streep; Oscar Isaac; Sundance festival; National Trust film locations | publisher=[[BBC Radio 4]] | work=[[The Film Programme]] | accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="Magical">{{cite news | title=Streep praises 'magical' park | work=[[Richmond and Twickenham Times]] | date=7 February 2014 | accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref>

As well as a location for films, Richmond Park is regularly featured in television programmes, corporate videos and fashion shoots. It has made an appearance on ''[[Blue Peter]]'', ''[[Inside Out (BBC TV series)|Inside Out]]'' (the BBC regional current affairs programme) and BBC ''[[Springwatch]]''.<ref name="Star"/> In 2014 it was featured in a video commissioned by [[Richmond Park#The Hearsum Collection|The Hearsum Collection]].<ref name="Hearsum video">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqzgc7b_Ky8 | title=The Heritage Pavilion Video | publisher=[[YouTube]] | date=11 November 2004 | accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>

==International connections==

There is a "[[:de:Schloss Richmond#Parkanlage|Richmond Park]]" in Germany.  The name is no coincidence.  It was created in 1768 in Brunswick for [[Princess Augusta of Great Britain|Princess Augusta]], sister of George III.  She was married to the [[Duke of Brunswick]] and was feeling homesick, so an English-style park was laid out and a palace built for her, both with the name "Richmond".<ref name="Brunswick">{{cite web | url=http://www.braunschweig.de/leben/im_gruenen/gruenanlagen/Rich_Ken.html | title=Schlo<U+00DF> Richmond-Park / Kennelgebiet | publisher=Braunschweig | accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref name="Peter Bessin">{{cite book | title=Der Regent als Architekt. Schlo<U+00DF> Richmond und die Lustschlo<U+00DF>bauten Braunschweig-Wolfenb<U+00FC>ttels zwischen 1680 und 1780 als Paradigma f<U+00FC>rstlicher Selbstdarstellung. |publisher=[[Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht]]|location=[[G<U+00F6>ttingen]] |year=2001 |ISBN= 3-525-47904-2  | author=Peter Bessin}}</ref> In 1935, the palace including the entire estate was purchased by [[Braunschweig|the City of Braunschweig]]. One condition for the purchase was that no structural changes ever be made and the park not be built on. The palace, which was rebuilt after the war, is now used for representational purposes.<ref name="Peter Bessin"/>

In 1864 [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]], Italian general and politician, visited Lord John Russell at Pembroke Lodge in 1864, <ref name= "Cloake 192"/> as did the Shah of [[Persia]], [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] in 1873. He was the first modern Iranian monarch to visit Europe.<ref name= "Cloake 192">Cloake, p. 192</ref> [[Faisal I of Iraq]] and [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] politician [[Salim Ali Salam]] were photographed visiting the park in 1925.

The first fallow deer introduced to [[New Zealand]] came from Richmond Park.<ref name="Ungulates">{{cite journal | url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Bio14Tuat02-t1-body-d3.html | title=Introduced ungulates in New Zealand <U+2013> (D) Fallow deer | publisher=[[Victoria University of Wellington]] | work=Tuatara | volume= 14|issue =2|date=July 1966 | accessdate=5 August 2013 | author=A. H. C. Christie and J. R. H. Andrews | pages=84}}</ref> In 1867 and 1876 fallow deer from the park were sent there to help build up stocks.<ref>Baxter Brown, p. 118</ref>

In 1953 [[Josip Broz Tito|President Tito]] of Yugoslavia stayed at White Lodge during a [[state visit]] to Britain.<ref name="FRP Guide130">{{cite book | title=Guide to Richmond Park | publisher=[[Richmond Park#Friends of Richmond Park|Friends of Richmond Park]]  | year=2011 | page=130|ISBN=978-0-9567469-0-0}}</ref>

